solution: The first cube root becomes $\sqrt[3]{9}$. $\sqrt[3]{8}=2$, so the second cube root becomes $\sqrt[3]{3}$. Multiplying these gives $\sqrt[3]{27} = \boxed{3}$.
chatgpt_solution:
We see that $1 + 8 = (1 + 2)(1 + 4) = 3 \cdot 5$, and $5$ is not divisible by any perfect cube other than $1$, so it cannot be simplified.

We also have $1+\sqrt[3]{8} = 1+\left(2^{\frac13}\right) = 1 + \frac21 = \frac32$.

So we have that
\[\sqrt[3]{1+8} \cdot \sqrt[3]{1+\sqrt[3]{8}} = \sqrt[3]{3 \cdot 5}\cdot\sqrt[3]{\frac32} = \sqrt[3]{\frac92(3)}=\boxed{\sqrt[3]{27} = \boxed{3}}.\]
